## Page-build conventions

### Design tokens (preserve verbatim)

```css
--bg:#0a0a0a; --bg-2:#111111; --bg-3:#161616;
--line:#222; --line-2:#2a2a2a;
--text:#f4f4f4; --muted:#8a8a8a; --muted-2:#b6b6b6;
--accent:#c6f24e;     /* lime accent — the studio signature */
--accent-soft:#f1ff9e;
--serif:"Instrument Serif","Cormorant Garamond",ui-serif,Georgia,serif;
--sans:"Inter",ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system,Segoe UI,Roboto,sans-serif;
--mono:"JetBrains Mono","IBM Plex Mono",ui-monospace,SFMono-Regular,Menlo,monospace;
--radius:18px; --radius-sm:10px; --maxw:1240px;
```

Per-case "after" frames get a tinted radial-gradient unique to the brand (lime/green = battery/EV; warm gold/amber = nuclear; teal-green = sister brand to a blue brand; cyan = healthcare AI; sunset orange = automotive/edge AI; violet = AI/compute; deep forest = climate; sage green = MRV; cool blue = manufacturing; warm amber/red = defence). Pick palettes so adjacent brands don't clash.

### Type styling

H1, section H2 and case-study H3 in `--serif`, weight 400, `letter-spacing:-.015em to -.02em`. All eyebrow labels, numbered prefixes, "BY THE NUMBERS" cells in `--mono`, `font-size:10–11px`, `text-transform:uppercase`, `letter-spacing:.1em–.15em`. Bullet lists use `●` (filled small circle) coloured `--accent`.

### Hero conventions

Industry tag pattern: `Industry · [Industry] · B2B Web Development & Design for [Industry] Companies` (Flow) or `Industry · [Industry] · Brand & Design for [Industry] Companies` (Design). H1 pattern: *"We design identity & develop websites, in 8–10 weeks, for [industry] brands."* The word for the industry sits inside `<em>` styled with `--accent`. 3-cell meta row: Positioning / Typical timeline (`8–10 wk`) / Status (`Premium Webflow Partner`). Live preview frame: pick the strongest client's live URL, `● LIVE` badge, plus a stat line below ("● N clients live · key VC names").

### Section structure (canonical order)

1. **Hero**
2. **Before/After** — 4–5 cards, monospace labels, branded "after" frame per company. Featured/marquee company can span full row.
3. **Problem section** — H2 (AEO question), 4-stat audit row (% failing some test, avg LCP, % using stock imagery, 0 zero-stat), 4-card pattern grid (`01 · Most common`).
4. **How We Help** — 4 columns, each with number + serif H3 + paragraph + bullet list + branded thumbnail.
5. **Case studies** — 4 to 10 cards, with `.featured` class for the marquee (full-width, two-column inside). Live URL bar, hero frame, industry tag, body copy, tag chips, 3-cell "by the numbers" (4-cell for featured), "Visit →" link. *"Currently shipping"* cards use a sub-heading "currently shipping" + 2026 + placeholder stats.
6. **Process** — 7 stages, each card has number / week / H4 / paragraph / 3-bullet list. **Each stage H4 must use industry-specific vocabulary**, never "Discovery / Strategy / Design / Development".
7. **Audience corners** — 6 cards covering sub-sectors. Each names a real client *"the [Client] pattern"*.
8. **Why us — engineers building for engineers** — narrative + accent-bordered POV box + 4-cell stats grid + 4-card engineer grid (3 mech engs in founder/3D/PM roles + 1 aerospace eng in web dev) + wide combo card below for strategy/design engineering-fluent partners (Sijeesh / Ekta / Zakia / Tanmaya).
9. **Team grid** — 10 members. Annotate engineering credentials on relevant roles for the industry context.
10. **Testimonials** — 4 cards, big serif blockquote with curly opening quote, brand label, attribution. Mark paraphrased placeholders clearly to the user.
11. **CTA section** — 2 columns: copy + calendar card with highlighted slot.
12. **Investors** — 4–5 cards. Include accent-bordered card for distinct partner types (e.g. Social Alpha as impact-deeptech incubator).
13. **Field note** — large serif quote panel with mono tag chips.
14. **Further reading** — link grid (★ for marquee/featured links, ↗ for others).
15. **FAQ section (AEO)** — 7–9 question-headline cards with bolded direct-answer sentences first.
16. **Footer** — 5-column layout, Bengaluru, India.

### AEO-formatted H2 patterns (apply everywhere)

Convert each section H2 to a question form an LLM would extract. The deeptech page does this with all 10 main H2s:

- "Same company. Same hardware. A very different website." → *"What does a [industry] website look like before and after a redesign?"*
- "Most [X] websites still look like..." → *"Why do most [industry] websites fail to communicate [Y]?"*
- "Four ways our team makes [X] websites impossible to ignore." → *"How does Everything Flow make a [industry] website stand out?"*
- "[N] websites for [N] very different [X] companies." → *"Which [industry] companies has Everything Flow built websites for?"*
- "[Stages name] — a 7-stage process built for [X]." → *"What is Everything Flow's 7-stage process for a [industry] website?"*
- "[N] corners of the [X] stack." → *"Which [industry] sub-sectors does Everything Flow serve?"*
- "A design studio built by engineers..." → *"Why is Everything Flow different from other [industry] web development agencies?"*
- "The [X] team behind your website" → *"Who works on a [industry] website at Everything Flow?"*
- "Trusted by [X] founders..." → *"What do [industry] founders say about working with Everything Flow?"*
- "We work with [X] companies funded by people you know." → *"Which VCs and partners back the [industry] companies Everything Flow works with?"*

### FAQ section pattern (LLM-extractable answers)

Add a dedicated FAQ section after Field-note / Further reading, before the footer. 7–9 cards, each with:

- H3 question (serif, weight 400, 24px)
- Answer paragraph: **first sentence is the direct, bolded factual answer**; rest is supporting evidence with named entities, statistics, client names.

Standard FAQs to include (adapt naming to destination):

