## Anti-patterns — do not do these

- Do not write generic process stage labels (*"Discovery / Strategy / Design / Development"*) — every stage H4 must use industry-specific vocabulary.
- Do not lead with fear-based or FUD messaging for cybersecurity, hooded-engineer imagery for deeptech, or any stock-cliché framing.
- Do not invent the founder/team's training credentials. The studio's training is *"design sustainability + comms design + mechanical engineering"* — do not name specific schools (KISD, etc.) unless the user confirms.
- Do not name "Social Alpha" or any partner generically — always tie to the specific partner type (e.g. Social Alpha as *"multi-stage incubator-foundation backing deeptech startups solving social-impact problems"*).
- Do not skip Gauge keyword research for BOTH destinations.
- Do not invent client outcomes. If using real clients, mark "by the numbers" stats as illustrative if you don't have real figures.
- Do not use multiple HTML/CSS files. One self-contained `.html` only.
- Do not use external image hosts the user can't see. Use CSS gradient frames + serif typography for placeholder brand visuals.
- Do not put "Webflow agency" in the title or hero of an Everything Flow web-development page. Webflow is the build stack, not the identifier. The exception is a page explicitly written about the Webflow practice itself.
- Do not confuse "GenRobotics" (parent, civic robotics) with "GenRobotics Medical" (the medical-robotics division — this is the one Everything Design worked on).
- Do not link the everything.design blog's CTA to everythingflow.agency. Route through everything.design/contact-us.

